Topics Reviewed
Input Validation & Application Security

Input Sanitization

Ensures user-supplied data is properly validated before processing

Prevents malicious input such as command injection attacks

Certificate Trust & PKI

SSL/TLS certificates may fail validation if the issuing CA is not trusted.

Installing the root or intermediate certificate allows the system/browser to verify the trust chain.

Security Monitoring

SIEM (Security Information and Event Management)

Centralizes log collection, correlation, and analysis

Provides real-time monitoring and alerting

Helps identify security incidents across multiple systems

Compliance & Risk Assessment

Gap Analysis

Identifies differences between current security practices and required standards

Helps organizations prioritize changes needed to meet regulatory or security requirements

Secure Data Transfer

Standard FTP does not provide encryption.

Secure alternatives include:

FTPS

SFTP

These protocols encrypt data during transmission to prevent interception.

Authentication vs Authorization

OAuth

Designed for authorization, not authentication

Uses tokens to grant applications limited access to resources on behalf of users

Commonly used for SSO and API access.

Social Engineering Threats

Phishing

A common tactic attackers use to obtain login credentials or sensitive information.

Security Operations Efficiency

Automation

Reduces repetitive security tasks

Improves response time and efficiency for security teams

Allows analysts to focus on higher-priority investigations.

Performance & Resource Monitoring

High resource usage (e.g., CPU near 99% or memory near capacity) can cause:

System slowdowns

Application instability

Delayed processing of requests.

